The Health Department has recorded 2 488 new COVID-19 cases, pushing the number of total infections to 1 484 900. There have been a further 237 COVID-19 related deaths in the country, bringing the national death toll to 47 382. In a statement, Health Minister Dr Zweli Mkhize says most of the new deaths were recorded in Gauteng. “Regrettably, we report 237 more COVID-19 related deaths: 46 from Eastern Cape, 25 from the Free State, 82 from Gauteng, 36 from KwaZulu-Natal, 12 from Limpopo, 19 from Mpumalanga and 17 from the Western Cape,” says Dr Mkhize. The total number of recoveries stands at 1 377 980. The cumulative total number of tests conducted to date is 8 605 729. 237 2 488 1 484 900 8 605 729 59 538 47 382 1 377 980 *As at 11 February 2021 1 425 362 (function(d){var js, id="pikto-embed-js", ref=d.getElementsByTagName("script")[0];if (d.getElementById(id)) { return;}js=d.createElement("script"); js.id=id; js.async=true;js.src="https://create.piktochart.com/assets/embedding/embed.js";ref.parentNode.insertBefore(js, ref);}(document)); As of today, the total number of confirmed #COVID19 cases is 1 484 900, the total number of deaths is 47 382 and the total number of recoveries is 1 377 980. pic.twitter.com/BsudawpJ1n — Dr Zweli Mkhize (@DrZweliMkhize) February 11, 2021 